module.exports = /*#__PURE__*/JSON.parse('[{"question":"Can a startup get business funding with no revenue?","answer":"Sometimes, but usually not through traditional banks. Early-stage founders with no revenue are more likely to rely on grants, crowdfunding, carefully managed personal-credit-led strategies, or smaller ecosystem-backed programs."},{"question":"Are business loans for new businesses realistic?","answer":"They can be, but it depends on how new, how documented, and how risky the profile looks. Many founders hear \'business loan\' and imagine a bank product that is actually designed for more mature businesses."},{"question":"What is credit stacking for startups?","answer":"Credit stacking is a strategy that uses multiple personal-credit-based lines or cards to create startup runway. It can be useful, but it is not risk-free and it requires disciplined management."},{"question":"When does revenue-based financing make sense?","answer":"It tends to make more sense for businesses with visible, consistent revenue and a strong use-of-funds case. It makes less sense when margins are thin or the founder is trying to solve a broken offer with expensive capital."},{"question":"Do microloans and grants matter if the amounts are smaller?","answer":"Yes. Smaller capital can still be strategically important when the goal is proving discipline, building operating history, or financing a clear next step without taking on an oversized repayment burden."},{"question":"What does Founder Fuel actually help with?","answer":"Founder Fuel helps founders understand realistic startup funding paths, qualification logic, tradeoffs, and next steps. It is an educational and conversion-oriented site, not a fake approval engine."}]');

