module.exports = /*#__PURE__*/JSON.parse('[{"slug":"startup-funding-no-revenue","title":"Startup Funding With No Revenue: What Is Actually Realistic?","excerpt":"If your startup has no revenue, your funding path is probably narrower than the internet makes it sound. Here is what is actually realistic and what usually is not.","category":"No-Revenue Funding","readTime":"7 min read","featured":true,"tags":["startup funding no revenue","grants","crowdfunding"],"sections":[{"heading":"The real problem","paragraphs":["No-revenue startups are usually trying to solve a profile mismatch with confidence. Traditional lenders care about repayment evidence, not founder enthusiasm.","That does not mean there are zero options. It means the options shift toward personal leverage, grants, crowdfunding, ecosystem support, or deliberate setup moves that improve future qualification."]},{"heading":"What tends to be more realistic","paragraphs":["Non-dilutive sources, community-backed programs, and carefully managed personal-credit-led runway are usually more realistic than generic business loans.","The key is knowing whether you need capital, proof, or better preparation first."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Microloans + grants","href":"/funding-options/microloans-grants/"},{"label":"Startup funding guide","href":"/startup-funding/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"}]},{"slug":"startup-funding-mistakes","title":"7 Startup Funding Mistakes That Burn Founders Early","excerpt":"Most bad capital decisions are not caused by bad intentions. They come from stage confusion, pressure, and chasing the wrong money for the wrong reason.","category":"Funding Mistakes","readTime":"8 min read","featured":true,"tags":["startup funding mistakes","qualification","cash flow"],"sections":[{"heading":"Mistake one: solving the wrong problem","paragraphs":["Some founders need margin repair, not capital. Others need proof, not debt. Capital cannot rescue a model that does not convert or a business that cannot explain where the money goes.","The earlier the business, the more important it is to define the use of funds in plain language."]},{"heading":"Mistake two: forcing bank logic on a startup-stage business","paragraphs":["The bank rejection is often not a personal insult. It is just a stage mismatch. Good founders lose time when they keep trying to force a traditional path before the profile is ready."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Credit stacking","href":"/funding-options/credit-stacking/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"},{"label":"Funding options hub","href":"/funding-options/"}]},{"slug":"startup-funding-by-stage","title":"Startup Funding by Stage: 0 to 24 Months","excerpt":"The best funding option changes as the company moves from setup to proof to operational maturity. This article maps what usually fits at each phase.","category":"By Stage","readTime":"6 min read","featured":true,"tags":["startup funding by stage","business credit for startups","microloans"],"sections":[{"heading":"Months 0 to 6","paragraphs":["This stage is about setup, proof, and discipline. Many founders need to slow down and create cleaner financial structure before they chase any capital path aggressively."]},{"heading":"Months 6 to 24","paragraphs":["This is where founder behavior starts to matter in underwriter language. Revenue consistency, business bank movement, bookkeeping, and use-of-funds clarity all get more important."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Revenue-based financing","href":"/funding-options/revenue-based-financing/"},{"label":"Startup funding guide","href":"/startup-funding/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"}]},{"slug":"bad-credit-startup-funding","title":"Bad Credit Startup Funding: What Founders Should Know Before Applying","excerpt":"Bad credit does not automatically end the search for capital, but it changes which routes are worth your time and which offers deserve skepticism.","category":"Credit Reality","readTime":"7 min read","featured":false,"tags":["bad credit startup funding","secured funding","microloans"],"sections":[{"heading":"What changes with weaker credit","paragraphs":["Weaker credit does not just change approval odds. It changes pricing, flexibility, and the amount of patience you need.","Founders with thin or bruised credit often do better by improving setup, seeking smaller community-backed products, or looking at secured structures rather than chasing shiny promises."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Microloans + grants","href":"/funding-options/microloans-grants/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"},{"label":"Insights","href":"/insights/"}]},{"slug":"business-credit-for-startups","title":"Business Credit for Startups: Build Readiness Before You Need It","excerpt":"Business credit is less about hacks and more about sequence, consistency, and credibility. Here is how early-stage founders should think about it.","category":"Business Credit","readTime":"9 min read","featured":true,"tags":["business credit for startups","credit building","qualification"],"sections":[{"heading":"What founders misunderstand","paragraphs":["Business credit is not a costume change. Registering the entity is not the same as becoming fundable. Issuers care about profile quality, operating behavior, and a coherent business picture.","Founders who treat business credit as a staged system tend to make better decisions than founders who treat it like a trick."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Credit stacking","href":"/funding-options/credit-stacking/"},{"label":"Startup funding guide","href":"/startup-funding/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"}]},{"slug":"predatory-lender-warnings","title":"Predatory Lender Warnings for Early-Stage Founders","excerpt":"When the business is stressed and cash is tight, bad capital can look like rescue. This article helps founders recognize the patterns before signing.","category":"Warnings","readTime":"5 min read","featured":false,"tags":["predatory lender warnings","revenue based financing","startup funding mistakes"],"sections":[{"heading":"Warning signs","paragraphs":["Guaranteed approvals, vague pricing, pressure-heavy sales language, and weak explanation of repayment mechanics are all red flags.","Founders should insist on clarity about total cost, repayment structure, use-of-funds fit, and what happens when revenue softens."]}],"relatedLinks":[{"label":"Revenue-based financing","href":"/funding-options/revenue-based-financing/"},{"label":"Funding mistakes","href":"/insights/startup-funding-mistakes/"},{"label":"Apply","href":"/apply/"}]}]');

